{"id":"1569566631","paper":{"title":{"text":"Lagrange Interpolation Polynomials and Generalized Reed-Solomon Codes over Rings of Matrices"},"authors":[{"name":"Li-Ping Wang"}],"abstr":{"text":"Abstract\u2013In this paper we ﬁrst give the Lagrange interpolation polynomials in rings of matrices over ﬁnite ﬁelds and propose a new secret sharing scheme similar to Shamir\u2019s secret sharing scheme as its direct application in cryptography. We also introduce the generalized Reed- Solomon codes over a noncommutative ring of matrices over a ﬁnite ﬁeld and study their properties using this interpolation formula. We show that they are maximum distance separable (MDS) and present the key equation by deriving their dual codes and Goppa formulation.\nKeywords\u2013Lagrange interpolation formula, codes over rings, quasi-cyclic codes, polynomial rings over matrix rings, secret sharing schemes"},"body":{"text":"Lagrange interpolation polynomials in ﬁnite ﬁelds have many applications such as Shamir\u2019s secret sharing scheme in cryptography [15] and coding theory [1], [2].\nIn this paper we generalize Lagrange interpolation poly- nomials in ﬁnite ﬁelds to those in rings of matrices over ﬁnite ﬁelds. As its direct application, we propose a new secret sharing scheme similar to Shamir\u2019s secret sharing scheme.\nAs we know, Lagrange interpolation formula in ﬁnite ﬁelds has close relationship with Reed-Solomon codes over ﬁnite ﬁelds and their generalizations, which are very useful in practice [8], [12], [17]. In the other hand, many results are about cyclic codes over rings such as integer residue rings, chain rings and p-adic rings [3], [4], [13], [14] and about quasi- cyclic codes [5], [6], [9], [10], [11]. In [7] authors viewed quasi-cyclic codes over a ﬁnite ﬁeld as cyclic codes over rings of matrices and proposed a new construction of some quasi- cyclic codes and self-dual codes.\nIn this paper we also introduce the generalized Reed- Solomon codes over a noncommutative ring of matrices over a ﬁnite ﬁeld and study their properties using this interpolation formula. We show that they are maximum distance separable (MDS) and present the key equation by deriving their dual codes and Goppa formulation.\nLet F q be a ﬁnite ﬁeld where q is a prime power and let M m ( F q ) denote the noncommutative ring of m × m matrices with entries in F q and M m ( F q )[X] denote the polynomials ring with coefﬁcients from M m ( F q ). In addition, we denote\nm × m zero matrix and the m × m identity matrix by 0 m and I m , respectively.\nAny polynomial with coefﬁcients over ﬁnite ﬁelds of degree less than n is uniquely determined by its values at n (or more) distinct points. This is the famous Lagrange interpolation polynomials in ﬁnite ﬁelds [15].\nNow we generalize the famous formula. First through- out this paper let n be a positive integer and let A = {A 1 , · · · , A n } be a subset of M m ( F q ) such that for any i ̸= j, A i − A j is invertible and A i A j = A j A i . For example,\n 0 0 1 1 0 1 0 1 0\nThen {I m , A, A 2 , · · · , A 6 } is a subset satisfying the above condition. In addition we suppose that the indeterminate X can commute with any matrix in M m ( F q ).\nTheorem 1: Let A be deﬁned as above. Then there exists a unique polynomial f (X) with degree less that n, i.e.,\nProof: First it is obvious that f (X) satisﬁes (1) with degree less than n. Assume g(X) ∈ M m ( F q )[X] also satisﬁes (1) and its degree is less than n.\nWithout the loss of generality, we assume the degree of f (X) −g(X) is n−1. The Euclidean division of f(X)−g(X) by X − A 1 , which is possible because X − A 1 is monic, is\nSince f (A 1 ) − g(A 1 ) = 0 m , we have r 1 (X) = 0 m . For i = 2, · · · , n, we get q 1 (A i ) = 0 m since f (A i ) − g(A i ) = 0 m and A i − A 1 is invertible.\nBased on the above theorem, we can construct a new secret sharing scheme similar to Shamir\u2019s secret sharing scheme.\nTheorem 2: Let A be deﬁned as above and an integer k, 1 ≤ k ≤ n. Let