g(X), and so h(X) ̸= 0 is also of degree less than k and let t be the number of the roots that h(X) has among {A 1 , · · · , A n }. The weight of codeword generated by h(X) must be no less than n − t. By Theorem 1 we get t ≤ k − 1 and so the minimum distance must be no less than n − k + 1. Let h(X) =\nand we can get a codeword of weight n − k + 1. Therefore the result is required.\nAs special linear codes, quasi-cyclic codes are the nat- ural generalization of cyclic codes. A linear code C of length n is called a quasi-cyclic code with index ℓ over F q if (c n −ℓ+1 , . . . , c n , c 1 , . . . , c n −ℓ ) ∈ C, for any c = (c 1 , . . . , c n ) ∈ C. It is well known that ℓ divides n and so we write n = mℓ. It is clear that C is cyclic if ℓ = 1.\nLet C be a linear code over M m ( F q ) and c = (c 1 , . . . , c n ) ∈ C. So we also can regard c as a codeword over F q if it is written as\nc = (c (1,1) 1 , · · · , c (1,m) 1 , c (2,1) 1 , · · · , c (2,m) 1 , · · · , c (m,m) 1 \t , · · · , · · ·\nwhere c (i,j) l denotes the (i, j)th entry of c l for 1 ≤ i, j ≤ m and 1 ≤ l ≤ n.\nCorollary 1: The generalized Reed-Solomon code GRS m,k (A, V) over M m ( F q ) is quasi-cyclic code over F q with index m 2 and its minimum distance is at least nm 2 − km 2 + m 2 .\nThe proof is forward result of Theorem 3 and is omitted here. Let y = (y 1 , . . . , y n ) and x = (x 1 , . . . , x n ) in M m ( F q ) n .\ny i x i . If C is an [n, k] linear code over M m ( F q ), its left dual code\nTheorem 4: If V further satisﬁes that V i B = BV i for any B ∈ M m ( F q ) and all i, 1 ≤ i ≤ n, the left dual of GRS n,k (A, V) is ⊥ GRS n,k (A, V) = GRS n,n −k (A, U),\n(A i − A j ) −1 . Proof: We need to prove that\nfor any f (X) ∈ M m ( F q )[X] k and g(X) ∈ M m ( F q )[X] n −k . So their product g(X)f (X) has degree at most n − 2. By Theorem 1, we have\nEquation the coefﬁcient of X n −1 from the two sides gives (3) and so the result is obtained.\nSet r = n − k. Let c = (c 1 , . . . , c n ) ∈ M m ( F q ) n and V satisfy the condition in Theorem 4. Then\nWe rewrite these r equations as a single equation in the polynomial ring M m ( F q )[Z] in a new indeterminate Z. The vector c is in C if and only if in M m ( F q )[Z] we have\nwe get the Goppa formulation for the generalized Reed- Solomon code GRS n,k (A, V) over M m ( F q ).\nTheorem 5: Let V satisfy the condition in Theorem 4. The generalized Reed-Solomon codes GRS n,k (A, V) over M m ( F q ) is equal to the set of all n-tuples c = (c 1 , · · · , c n ) with c i ∈ M m ( F q ) such that\nOnce we have Goppa formulation for for the generalized Reed-Solomon code GRS n,k (A, V) over M m ( F q ) and we suppose that the subset A satisﬁes that A i B = BA i for all B ∈ M m ( F q ), it is easy to get the key equation.\nSuppose c = (c 1 , . . . , c n ) is a transmitted codeword, r = (r 1 , . . . , r n ) is the received word and e = (e 1 , . . . , e n ) is the error pattern. So we have r = c + e. Calculate the syndrome polynomial of r:\nLet B = {i| e i ̸= 0} be the set of error locations. Then we have the syndrome polynomial\nNow we drop the subscripts and write S(Z) for the syn- drome polynomial.\nDecoding problem can be reduced to matrix feedback shift register synthesis problem. In [16] such a algorithm has been given and so studying decoding problem is our future work.\nThe research was supported in part by National Natural Science Foundation of China (Grant No. 10990011 and No. 61170289) and the Strategic Priority Research Program of Chinese Academy of Sciences under Grant XDA06010702. The author also would like to thank the reviewers for their helpful suggestions and comments."},"refs":[{"authors":[{"name":"A. Arman"}],"title":{"text":"Generalized Rational Interpolation Over Commutative Rings and Remainder Decoding, IEEE Trans"}},{"authors":[{"name":"S. R. Blackbur"}],"title":{"text":"Fast rational interpolation, Reed-Solomon decoding, and the linear complexity proﬁle of sequences, IEEE Trans"}},{"authors":[{"name":"A. Bon